      <body>
         <div type="edition" xml:lang="pra-Latn" rendition="class:83225 maturity:83209">
             <p>
                 <lb n="1"/>manikārasa mahamar<unclear>i</unclear>tino sabhāriyasa saputakasa sadu<unclear>h</unclear><supplied reason="lost">utakasa</supplied> <unclear>sajā</unclear>mātukasa dāna cetiya pu<unclear>pha</unclear>gaha
                 <lb n="2" break="no"/>nik<unclear>a</unclear>
             </p>
         </div>
         <div type="apparatus">
             <listApp>
                 <app loc="1-2">
                     <lem>cetiya pu<unclear>pha</unclear>gahanika</lem>
                     <rdg source="bib:Nakanishi+Hinuber2014_01"><unclear>cetiyapu</unclear><supplied reason="lost">pha</supplied><unclear>gaha</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ni</supplied></rdg>
                     <note>who seem to have missed the two <foreign>akṣaras</foreign> engraved below line 1, for lack of space.</note>
                 </app>
             </listApp>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" resp="part:vito">
             <p>A shrine<supplied reason="subaudible">-bearing slab and a?</supplied> <foreign>pupphagahani</foreign>: the gift of the jeweller Mahāmariti, together with his wife, his son<supplied reason="subaudible">s</supplied>, his daughter<supplied reason="subaudible">s</supplied>, and his son<supplied reason="subaudible">s</supplied>-in law.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
             <p>As remarked by <bibl><ptr target="bib:Nakanishi+Hinuber2014_01"/><citedRange unit="page">47</citedRange></bibl>, Mahāmariti occurs as the donor of a drum-slab bearing a representation of a shrine and referred to as <foreign>cediya</foreign> in <ref target="DHARMA_INSKnI00093.xml">KnI0093</ref>. Here, the <foreign>pupphagahani</foreign> does not bear any such representation, so the meaning of <foreign>cetiya pu<unclear>pha</unclear>gahanika</foreign> is a bit puzzling. I therefore suppose this phrasing may jointly refer to the two structural elements dedicated by the donor, and translate accordingly.</p>
         </div>
